rguing that these generic separations grew out of an increasing preoccupation with the cultivation and control of interiorized spirituality, God Made Word shows that by tracing certain mystic representations we come to understand the emergence of different discursive rules and expectations for a wide range of representations of the ineffable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMysticism and literaturezSpainxHistory. 0aMysticism in literature. 0aMysticismzSpainxHistory. 0aSpanish literatureyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aEarly modern Spain.  aInquisition.  aSpanish literature.  aTeresa of Ávila.  aalumbradismo.  amystic literature.  amystic poetry.  amysticism on stage.  amysticism.  aprayer manuals.  arecogimiento.  aspiritual autobiography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148752881240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487528812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487528812/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK